AGI - Lidia Lominovska, 97 years old, marched for hours and hours, looking for shelter, after the Russians bombed his village of Ocheretyne, in the Donetsk oblast. Wearing a colorful scarf around the wrinkled face, the fragile but resistant woman told her exhausting escape, on foot, about 10 kilometers in the eastern region of the country. "I walked long. I walked and walked and I was tired... My God!>", he said, calmly remembering the chaos of the last days after I fled, last Friday. "I continued to go and go," she told AFP from her bed in a refuge in nearby Pokrovsk. Russia is pushing west into the Donetsk region since, in February, it conquered Avdiivka, witness of some of the worst battles of the two years of Moscow offensive and central knot in these stages of guerrilla wars.
&nbsp;
In recent days, fighting in Ocheretyne was intensified, part of which would be under Russian control. Moscow also conquered other villages in the area. The commander-in-chief of Ukraine, Oleksandr Syrsky, reported on Sunday that the situation on the front was "fighting", as Russian troops had exploited an advantage in terms of men and weapons to advance. "I suffered so much!", explained Lominovska, who left everything behind and fled from his home of Ocheretyne, which before the war had about 3,000 inhabitants. "God knows who was bombing. I didn't see anyone. I just heard something explode. I didn't know where it was or what it was," he explained. For these reasons he decided to leave, bumping into the bodies of the fallen soldiers as he walked away from his village, now largely in ruins. "Almost everything was on fire... The Russians burned so many houses."
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"But you know, I was walking and there was no one anywhere. I just heard the gunshots. I thought they'd shoot me walking." Using a piece of table, now destroyed, as a stick, Lominovska continued along a path that leads to Pokrovsk, about 30 kilometers west of Ocheretyne. After a little he also lost the sense of time. "I didn't have a watch, I had nothing."
He was walking alone for several hours when two Ukrainian soldiers stopped their car and one asked: "Where are you going?".&nbsp;"I go to where I can go, then I will fall into the grass and spend the night there," said Lominovska. "The soldiers gave me two sandwiches. I ate one. I no longer had the strength to consume anything else," he added.&nbsp; The troops then called the law enforcement forces to give her a ride to Pokrovsk. The regional police spokesman, Pavlo Dyachenko, said that Lominovska "walked a distance of about 10 kilometers".
&nbsp;
On Sunday, the incessant heavy blows of the Russians targeted the area and in the sky appeared gray smoke plums, according to a reporter of the AFP in the village of Vozdvizhenka. Two residents were evacuated by the members of a special police unit nicknamed Angeli Bianchi, said Dyachenko that&nbsp; he feels like Lominovska was one of the last people to leave his village, which according to him is now destroyed. "Some are still there, but we do not know their number, nor whether they are alive or dead," he added. Even in the villages surrounding the situation is very difficult, because "the bombing of the enemy does not stop".
