AGI - The efforts of international diplomacy are intensified to try to reach an agreement between Israel and Hamas for the release of hostages and for a ceasefire in Gaza.» On Sunday evening, US President Joe Biden called Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu, in a last attempt to avoid the offensive on Rafah > and to foster an understanding that breaks the Strip, devastated by hunger and famine after almost seven months of war. Biden and Netanyahu, read in a White House note at the end of the call, "examined ongoing talks to ensure the release of hostages and an immediate ceasefire in Gaza." Biden, we read again, "referring to his statement with 17 other world leaders asking that Hamas releases his citizens without delay to ensure a ceasefire and aid to the people of Gaza."
&nbsp;
On the table there is the proposal of Tel Aviv and Cairo for a ceasefire on which, according to statements by senior officials of Hamas, there should be no "important problems", > provided that it is not Israel to put new obstacles. Hamas has announced that he will officially respond to the proposal today and, precisely for this reason, the efforts of the mediators, including the US, are strengthening. A delegation of the Islamist movement, led by Khalil al Hayya>, vice of Hamas leader in Gaza Yahya Sinwar, will arrive in Egypt > in a climate so more positive perhaps of the past and, according to Axios, also from Israeli is the first time in almost seven months of war that leaders say they are available to discuss the end of the war.
&nbsp;
An exponent of the Palestinian faction's political office said that the new proposal for a ceasefire in Gaza "is still being studied". The draft stipulates that in the first phase of the Hamas agreement will release 33 hostages - among women, sick, elderly and over 50 - while Israel will release Palestinian prisoners, including some who have been convicted of terrorism. In addition, a certain Palestinian movement will be allowed towards the north of Gaza and a gradual, limited withdrawal of Israeli troops from certain positions within the Strip. Finally, there will be negotiations for a complete cessation of hostilities which will not happen until its objectives have been achieved.
<div </div
The American Secretary of State Antony Blinken is at Riad>, the first stage of a new round of talks that will also take him to Jordan and Israel>, Blinken meets in the Saudi capital Arab and European Foreign Ministers visiting the Gulf to discuss the plans of the "day after" for the reconstruction of post-war Gaza, said an official of the State Department.
&nbsp;
At Riad, the US Secretary of State expressed the hope that Hamas accepts the proposal for an agreement on Gaza, which is called "extraordinaryly generous". &nbsp;&nbsp; "Hamas has an extraordinarily generous proposal from Israel," Blinken said, "at this moment, the only thing between the people of Gaza and a ceasefire is Hamas." "They must decide and decide quickly. I hope they make the right decision and we can have a fundamental change in dynamics," added the head of American diplomacy, which reiterated its no to the offensive on Rafah planned by Israel.&nbsp; "We have not yet seen a plan that allows us to believe that civilians can be effectively protected," he explained.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
In the last few hours some Israeli sources have again faded the hopes of a truce. "The preparations for Rafah continue," he said, and, even with an agreement on the hostages, "Israel will not give up his war goals." The Israeli government is facing increasing internal and international pressure to reach an agreement. A pressure that is putting more and more on the Netanyahu wall, weakened also by an internal confrontation in the country. The Minister of War Cabinet Benny Gantz, said that if the government rejects the hostage agreement, supported by security services, "it will not have the right to continue to exist". "The return of our hostages, abandoned by the government on October 7, is urgent," Gantz wrote on Telegram.
&nbsp;
Statements that come after the Minister of Finance, Bezalel Smotrich, warned that the government that will not have "no right to existence" unless Israel invades Rafah. In a post on X, the leader of the far-right party rejected the agreement mediated by Egypt with Hamas to recover the dozens of Israeli hostages in Gaza in exchange for Palestinian hostages and resize the Israeli offensive, calling it a "humious surrender" to the Nazis on the shoulders of hundreds of IDF soldiers who died. In the words of Smotrich echoed the Minister of extreme right Itamar Ben Gvir, who tweeted that "a reckless agreement is equivalent to the dissolution of the government".
&nbsp;
The Israeli authorities estimate that there are still 129 hostages held in Gaza*, 34 of which are dead. The last truce at the end of November allowed the exchange of 80 hostages with 240 Palestinian prisoners. &nbsp;
